        <div class="guide-content">
            
            <!-- Software Introduction -->
            <section class="mb-5">
                <h2 class="text-primary mb-3"><i class="fas fa-laptop-medical"></i> About BiliTool.Vn</h2>
                <p>
                    <strong>BiliTool.Vn</strong> is a web-based medical calculator designed to support pediatricians, neonatologists, and healthcare professionals in assessing, monitoring, and decision-making for neonatal jaundice (including preterms thanks to the combined algorithm).
                </p>
                <p>
                    The system provides an end-to-end workflow from inputting clinical parameters (age in hours, total serum bilirubin, gestational age, and neurotoxicity/clinical risk factors), precisely calculating intervention thresholds (Phototherapy, Exchange Transfusion), and visualizing trend data over time (Trend Chart). In particular, the system handles parallel calculations under multiple protocols to deliver the safest possible clinical recommendation.
                </p>
                <div class="card bg-light border-0 shadow-sm mt-4">
                    <div class="card-body">
                        <h5 class="text-danger"><i class="fas fa-book-medical"></i> Scientific Basis (Dual-Protocol)</h5>
                        <p class="mb-2 mt-2">
                            All algorithms, mathematical configurations, and clinical recommendations are built upon rigorous validation and cross-referencing of 2 leading international guidelines:
                        </p>
                        <ul class="mb-0">
                            <li class="mb-2">
                                <strong>American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP 2022):</strong><br/>
                                <a href="https://publications.aap.org/pediatrics/article/150/3/e2022058859/188726/Clinical-Practice-Guideline-Revision-Management-of" target="_blank" class="text-decoration-none">
                                    <em>"Clinical Practice Guideline Revision: Management of Hyperbilirubinemia in the Newborn Infant 35 or More Weeks of Gestation" (Pediatrics, Sept 2022).</em>
                                </a>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <strong>UK National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE CG98):</strong><br/>
                                <a href="https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg98" target="_blank" class="text-decoration-none text-success">
                                    <em>"Jaundice in newborn babies under 28 days" (Updated October 2023).</em>
                                </a>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <hr class="my-5" />

